title: English Baccalaureate (EBacc) achievement for children aged 14 to 16 (key stage 4)
measure_summary:
This data measures the number of pupils achieving the [English Baccalaureate](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/english-baccalaureate-ebacc/english-baccalaureate-ebacc#ebacc-subjects) (EBacc) by ethnic group. It also shows each ethnic group’s share of achieving EBacc by percentage. 

The data covers the academic year 2015/16 (September 2015 to July 2016).

The EBacc is a school performance measure. It allows people to see how many pupils get a grade C or above in the core academic subjects (English, Maths, Science, a language, and History or Geography) at key stage 4 in any government-funded school. It was first introduced into the performance tables in the 2009 academic year.

Key stage 4 covers school years 10 and 11, when children are aged 14 to 16.
summary:
* in 2015/16, there were 540,689 pupils in key stage 4 at maintained schools in England, of which ethnicity was known for 534,918 (99%)

* 79% were White, 10% were Asian, 5% were Black, 4% were Mixed, 0.4% were Chinese, and 1.5% were from the any Other ethnic group

* Chinese pupils were the most likely to achieve the EBacc

* Gypsy/Roma children were least likely to achieve the EBacc 

* across all ethnic groups, girls were more likely to achieve the EBacc than boys

* across all ethnic groups, pupils eligible for free school meals (FSM) were less likely to achieve the EBacc than those not eligible
need_to_know:
Please be aware that some of the statistics quoted here for some ethnic groups are based on very small numbers of pupils and are highly variable over time.

Attainment is lower for children from a Traveller of Irish heritage background – however, there were only 122 pupils from this background in key stage 4 in 2015/16, a much smaller number than for other ethnic groups (for example, there were 20,434 Pakistani pupils in key stage 4). Therefore, data comparisons between Traveller of Irish Heritage pupils and other ethnic groups may be unreliable.

The ethnicity of 1.1% of pupils (5,771) is not accounted for. This includes pupils whose ethnicity was not surveyed, pupils who refused to be surveyed, and pupils whose ethnicity could not be determined. 

Any unapproved qualifications, such as unregulated international GCSEs, are not included in this data. Therefore, this data does not represent all qualifications taken by pupils, only those approved by the English Baccalaureate (EBacc), which count towards the secondary school performance tables. The figures vary between ‘all schools’ and ‘state schools’ mainly due to the impact of unregulated international GCSEs taken in independent schools.

In the published ‘statistical first release’ (SFR) for EBacc achievement, the Department of Education (DfE) has ‘suppressed’ very small numbers (for example, values of 1 or 2, a percentage based on 1 or 2 pupils who achieved, or 0, 1 or 2 pupils who did not achieve a particular level).
This is because, where the size of the ethnic group population is small enough that an individual’s identity could come to light, information is excluded, or 'suppressed', to preserve confidentiality. This is consistent with DfE’s [statistical policy statement on confidentiality](https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/190768/Confidentiality_Policy_v4.pdf).

Data for some Muslim and Sikh schools was not included in the statistics for faith schools because the small numbers of pupils make it impossible to draw meaningful conclusions about their attainment. Data for faith schools is also only provided for pupils in state-funded mainstream schools.
ethnicity_definition_summary:
This data uses categories from the Department of Education’s school census, which is broadly based on the 2001 national census, with three exceptions:  

* Traveller of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma children have been separated into two categories
* Sri Lankan has been added to the Asian/Asian British group but is not reported separately
* Chinese pupils have been assigned a separate category

These changes were made after consultations with local authorities and lobby groups. 

The categories in the school census are as follows:

White:

* White British
* White Irish
* Traveller of Irish Heritage
* Gypsy/Roma
* Other White

Mixed/Multiple ethnic groups:

* White and Black Caribbean
* White and Black African
* White and Asian
* Other Mixed background

Asian/Asian British:

* Indian
* Pakistani
* Bangladeshi
* Sri Lankan
* Other Asian background

Black/African/Caribbean/Black British:

* Black African
* Black Caribbean
* Other Black background

Chinese

Other ethnic group

Information is provided for both detailed and broad ethnic groups categories where possible and when the data is available.

The 6 broad categories used are as follows:

* White
* Mixed/Multiple ethnic groups
* Asian/Asian British
* Black/African/Caribbean/Black British
* Other ethnic group
* Chinese

However, region, local authority, school admission, school type, special education needs (SEN) and religion of school data is only provided for 5 broad ethnic groups. Information about the specific ethnic categories is excluded to preserve confidentiality and ensure individuals cannot be identified. Information about the Other ethnic group is not given because DfE does not publish data for this group at these levels.

The 5 broad categories are as follows:

* White
* Mixed/Multiple ethnic groups
* Asian/Asian British
* Black/African/Caribbean/Black British
* Chinese
data_source_purpose: The main purpose is to measure schools and pupil performance at key stage 4 (GCSE) to monitor and improve standards and inform parental choice.
methodology:
The key stage 4 datasets are compiled using information matched together from 3 data sources:
prior attainment records (key stage 2 results) 
school census records 
qualification entries and results collected from awarding bodies 

Key stage 4 data received from awarding bodies is combined with pupil characteristics from the school census and prior attainment by the department’s contractor. 

Records are matched, using identifiers such as surname, forename, date of birth, unique pupil number (UPN), gender and postcode. This successfully matches around 98% of results. 

The statistics in this commission cover the data collated for the 2016 secondary school performance tables. The performance tables and the related statistical first release report results are based on pupils at the end of key stage 4, who are typically aged 15 at the start of the academic year. 
The coverage of the local authority (LA) and regional statistics is state-funded schools only in England. This includes city technology colleges and academies but excludes hospital schools, pupil referral units and alternative provision.

Pupils are included in the figures for FSM if their families have claimed eligibility for FSM at the time of the annual spring school census. This FSM definition includes all who were eligible to receive free school meals, not only those who actually received free school meals. Pupils not eligible for free school meals or unclassified pupils are described as ‘All other pupils’.                  
Parents are able to claim FSM if they receive a [qualifying benefit.](https://www.gov.uk/apply-free-school-meals)

FSM is used as an indicator of disadvantage, but when drawing conclusions, it should be remembered that not all eligible parents apply for FSM and families who don’t quite reach the eligibility threshold for FSM may still be suffering deprivation.
suppression_rules:
Values of 1 or 2, or a percentage based on 1 or 2 pupils who achieved; or 0, 1 or 2 pupils who did not achieve a particular level are suppressed in circumstances where non-suppression would lead to disclosure of pupils. 

Some additional figures have been suppressed to prevent the possibility of a suppressed figure being revealed.

This suppression is consistent with our Statistical policy statement on confidentiality.

Schools are able to apply for pupils to be removed from their figures, if they have recently arrived from overseas and their first language is not English. We allow the removal of these pupils from the school and local authority figures as they can have an impact on some schools’ figures (since some schools have significant numbers of such pupils). However, we continue to include these pupils in the national figures so that they reflect the attainment of all pupils. Schools can also apply for pupils to be removed if a pupil has been admitted following a permanent exclusion from another school, if the pupil is not at the end of key stage 4, if the pupil has permanently left England, or the pupil is deceased. It may not be appropriate for schools to be held accountable for these pupils and therefore with adequate evidence we allow the removal of them so they are not included in the school's performance measures
disclosure_control:
The Code of Practice for Official Statistics requires DfE to take reasonable steps to ensure that their published or disseminated statistics protect confidentiality.

For more information about DfE’s disclosure control procedures for its statistical releases please see [DfE’s statistical policy statement on confidentiality](https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/190768/Confidentiality_Policy_v4.pdf)
estimation: Percentages in the tables and charts are given to nearest whole number and are given to one decimal place in the downloads.

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity
dimensions.summary:
This data shows that:

* nationally, around a quarter of pupils achieved the EBacc in key stage 4

* looking at the broad ethnic groups, 52% of Chinese pupils, 31% of Asian and Other pupils and 27% of Mixed pupils achieved the EBacc – all above the national average of 25% 

* 24% of White pupils and 23% of Black pupils achieved the EBacc – both below the national average of 25% 

* Looking at the detailed ethnic groups, Gypsy/Roma, Irish Traveller, Black Caribbean, White and Black Caribbean, Other Black, Pakistani and White British pupils were all below the national average

* 1% of Gypsy/Roma pupils achieved the EBacc – the lowest percentage of any group

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity and eligibility for free school meals (FSM)
dimensions.summary:
Eligibility for FSM is used as an indicator of deprivation by the Department of Education. For more about who qualifies for FSM see Methodology. 

The data shows that:

* 72,528 pupils (13%) were eligible for FSM in key stage 4 in 2015/16

* the breakdown of pupils eligible for FSM at the end of key stage 4 is: 11% of White pupils, 19% of Mixed ethnic pupils, 18% of Asian pupils, 23% of Black pupils, 4% of Chinese pupils, and 25% of pupils from any other ethnic background

* 10% of pupils eligible for FSM achieved the EBacc, compared to 27% of pupils who were not eligible

* the Chinese ethnic group had the highest percentage of FSM-eligible pupils achieving the EBacc (42%)

* White British FSM-eligible pupils were least likely to achieve the EBacc, with 6% doing so, compared to 27% of non-eligible White British pupils 

* Irish pupils saw the largest difference between the groups, at 28 percentage points, with 10% of FSM-eligible pupils achieving the EBacc, compared to 38% of those not eligible doing so

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity and area
dimensions.summary:
The data shows that:

* Kingston upon Thames in London had the highest percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc (49%)

* Blackpool in the North West had the lowest percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc (9%)

* the percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc was highest for White pupils in Hammersmith and Fulham in London (51%), for Mixed pupils in Kingston-upon-Thames in London (58%), for Asian pupils in Sutton in London (75%), for Black pupils in Wigan in the North West (56%), and for Chinese pupils in Sunderland in the North East, North Lincolnshire in Yorkshire and the Humber and Walsall in the West Midlands (100%)

* the percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc was lowest for White pupils in Blackpool in the North West (9%) and Leicester (9%) in the East Midlands, for Mixed pupils in Stoke-on-Trent in the West Midlands (7%), for Asian pupils in Oldham in the North West (14%), for Black pupils in Derby in the East Midlands (6%) and Oldham in the North West (6%) and for Chinese pupils in Waltham Forest in London (14%)

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity and gender
dimensions.summary:
The data shows that:

* overall, more girls (30%) achieved the EBacc than boys (20%)

* of the broad ethnic groups, Chinese girls (60%) and boys (44%) had the highest percentage achieving the Ebacc

* 16% of Black boys achieved the Ebacc, making Black boys the least likely pupils within the broad ethnic groups to do so

* of the specific ethnic groups, Black Caribbean boys were least likely to achieve the EBacc, with 10% doing so

* pupils from the any Other Asian background showed the largest difference between boys and girls for pupils achieving the EBacc, at 17 percentage points, with 47% of girls doing so compared to 30% of boys

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity, gender and free school meals (FSM)
dimensions.summary:
Eligibility for FSM is used as an indicator of deprivation by the Department of Education. To learn more about who qualifies for FSM see  Methodology.

The data shows that:

* overall, 13% of girls eligible for FSM achieved the EBacc, compared to 8% of boys

* Chinese girls had the highest percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc (57%) and White British, Black Caribbean and Mixed White and Black Caribbean boys the lowest (5%)

* Chinese pupils eligible for FSM showed the biggest difference, at 30 percentage points, between boys and girls among pupils achieving the EBacc: 57% of girls achieved compared to 27% of boys

* White British and Irish pupils eligible for FSM showed the smallest difference between boys and girls among pupils achieving the EBacc

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity, gender and area
dimensions.summary:
The data shows that:

* the percentage of girls achieving the EBacc was higher than boys in every local authority, where data is available

* for White pupils, the biggest gap between boys and girls achieving the EBacc was found in Westminster, where there was a 30 point difference 
for Chinese pupils, the biggest gap between boys and girls achieving the EBacc was found in Warwickshire (60 percentage points); for Black pupils, Norfolk (42 percentage points); for Asian pupils, Gateshead (37 percentage points); and for Mixed pupils, Camden (32 percentage points)

* please be aware except for the information for White and Mixed pupils, the statistics quoted here for EBacc achievement by ethnic group, gender and local authority are based on small numbers of pupils and are highly variable over time

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity, gender and basis for school admission
dimensions.summary:
This data groups [schools by admission type](https://www.gov.uk/types-of-school) into the following 3 categories, according to whether they select their pupils by ability:

* selective schools
* non-selective schools in highly selective areas (where 25% or more of state-funded secondary places are in state-funded selective schools) 
* all other non-selective schools (including schools in local authorities with some selection, as well as those with no selection)   

The data shows that:

* in 2015/16, 22,512 of pupils (4%) in key stage 4 were in selective schools, 34,658 (7%) in non-selective schools in highly selective areas, and 472,525 (89%) in non-selective schools in other areas

* girls performed better than boys across all types of school and ethnic group, except Chinese girls in non-selective schools in highly selective areas

* Chinese girls in selective schools had the highest percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc (88%)

* White boys  and boys from a Mixed ethnic background in non-selective schools in highly selective areas had the lowest percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc (10%)

* Black pupils in non-selective schools in highly selective areas showed the largest gap between girls and boys, at 20 percentage points, with 31% of girls achieving the EBacc, compared to 11% of boys

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity and type of school
dimensions.summary:
* 35% of pupils were in local authority maintained mainstream schools, 62% were in academies and free schools, 2% were in state-funded special schools and 0.2% in further education colleges in 2015/16

* overall, there were 530,580 pupils in state-funded mainstream schools, of whom 78% were White, 4% were Mixed, 10% were Asian, 5% were Black and 0.4% were Chinese

* looking at all state-funded mainstream schools, Chinese pupils were most likely to achieve the EBacc,with 52% doing so, and Black pupils least likely, with 23% doing so

* the lowest achieving in Free schools were Black pupils, with 10% achieving the EBacc in these schools

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity, special education needs (SEN) and gender
dimensions.summary:
Pupils with special education needs (SEN) have learning difficulties or disabilities that make it harder for them to learn than most children of the same age. 

Since 2015, pupils have been categorised as follows:                                                             

* no identified SEN                                                                                                                           
* SEN support: extra or different help is given from that provided as part of the school's usual curriculum, and the class teacher and SEN coordinator (SENCO) may receive advice or support from outside specialists
* SEN statement or education, health and care (EHC) plan: a pupil is given a SEN statement or an EHC plan once a formal assessment has been made                                                            
 
‘All SEN pupils’ refers to the total number of pupils with either SEN support, a SEN statement or an EHC plan. 

The data shows that:

* in 2015/16, there were 78,682 pupils at the end of key stage 4 with SEN: 80% were White, 7% were Asian, 6% were Black, 4% were Mixed and 0.2% were Chinese

* of the 78,682 SEN students in total, 74% had SEN support and 26% had SEN with a statement or EHC plan

* of all SEN pupils, Chinese pupils were most likely to achieve the EBacc (12%), while White and Black pupils were least likely (5%)

* of pupils with SEN support, Chinese were the most likely to achieve the EBacc (12%), while Black and White pupils were least likely (6%)

* of SEN pupils with a statement or EHC plan, Chinese had the highest percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc (13%), while White, Black and Mixed pupils had the lowest (2%)

dimensions.title: EBacc achievement by ethnicity, gender and religion of school
dimensions.summary:
This data divides schools into the following religious categories:

* no religious character 
* Church of England schools 
* Roman Catholic schools
* Other Christian faith schools (including those of mixed denomination or other Christian beliefs, for example, Greek Orthodox)
* Jewish schools
* Muslim schools
* Sikh schools

The data shows that:

* in 2015/16, there were 530,580 key stage 4 pupils in state-funded mainstream schools in England

* 82% of pupils attended schools with with no religious character, 6% attended Church of England schools, 10% attended Roman Catholic schools, 2% attended Other Christian faith schools, 0.2% attended Jewish, 0.1% attended Muslim and 0.03% attended Sikh schools

* Muslim schools had the highest percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc, with 51% of all pupils and 53% of Asian pupils doing so, making Asian pupils the highest achieving group at this type of school 

* Black pupils at schools with no religious character and other Christian faith schools had the lowest percentage of pupils achieving the EBacc, with 22% of all pupils doing so

* of all pupils, Chinese girls at Other Christian faith schools were most likely to achieve the EBacc, with 77% doing so

* of all pupils, Black boys at Other Christian faith schools were least likely to achieve the EBacc, with 15% doing so
